PREFACE.

The first instalment of the long-announced MƒÅnasollƒÅsa, otherwise known as the Abhila·π£itƒÅrthachintƒÅma·πái, which purports to have been composed by the great Western Chalukya King Bh≈´lokamalla Some≈õvara, son of VikramƒÅditya VI, is now offered to the public. It is a voluminous work, extending to about 8000 Granthas, and is divided into five Vi·πÉ≈õatis, each containing 20 Adhy»Éyas or chapters of unequal length, some chapters again including several sub- sections. The whole work is thus divided into one hundred chapters, dealing with one hundred different topics on the necessities and written for the instruction of the members of royal families. The first volume represents two among the five Vi·πÉ≈õatis, and comprises 40 Adby»Éyas or chapters.

The present edition is based on the following five MSS:

A. Belonging to the BARODA CENTRAL LIBRARY. It is a complete press-copy prepared with the help of three MSS.

B. Belonging to the Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona. It contains 109 leaves and is, though incomplete, a very good copy.

C. Complete, though recent.

D. Complete, written in ≈öaka 1592. Leaves are very brittle and the MS requires very careful handling. It offers good readlings.

E. Incomplete; in the middle about 50 leaves are wanting. It is older than D. On the last leaves the ink has faded.

The last three MSS belong to the Bikaner Durbar.

The authorship of the MƒÅnasollƒÅsa is attributed, in the 9th ≈õloka on page 2 and the colophon, to the Chalukya King Some≈õvara, surnamed Bh≈´lokamalla and SatyƒÅ≈õrayakulatilaka. A reference to ≈õloka 371 on page 62 will, however, make it evident that this attribution is incorrect. In this ≈õloka Somesvara is himself made the standard of comparison, and no anthor would be guilty of so flagrant a piece of vanity. It is therefore probable that the book was composed in his Court by some prodigiously learned and well-informed man, thoroughly acquainted with the royal household, royal necessities and royal whims.*

King Some≈õvara is the son of VikramƒÅditya VI, and belongs to the line of the Western Chalukyas whose capital was at KalyƒÅni. Aufrecht in his Catalogus Catalogorum fixes the period of his reign as 1127-1138. In Barnett’s Antiquities of India the date is 1126-1138. The date of composition of this work seems to be 1052 ≈öaka (1131 A. D.) as the ≈õloka 61 on page 34 while giving the DhruvƒÅ·πÖka mentions Friday as the first day of the month of Chaitra when the ≈öaka year 1051 had elapsed.

It is generally believed that Some≈õvara ascended the throne in A. D. 1127; but the inscription recording the grant of land made by MahƒÅm·πádale≈õvara M√¢rasi·πÉhadevarasa to the temple of MƒÅ·πáikyadeva containing an image of Eka≈õƒÅleya P√¢r≈°vanƒÅtha in the 6th year of the reign of Some≈õvara Bh≈´lokamalla in the year ≈öaka (1052 corresponding to A.D. 1130-31) shows that the date of his accession cannot be 1127; it must be 1124-25. The real date of Some≈õvara’s accession therefore is a matter of controversy which may better be left in the hands of the historians and antiquarians for solution. The date of accession, whether 1124 or 1127, does not, however, materially come in conflict with the date given as DhruvƒÅnka in the MƒÅnasollƒÅsa already mentioned.

Some scholars are under the impression that A. D. 1127 is the date of composition of the MƒÅnasollƒÅsa. But this appears from the above, and also from other considerations, to be incorrect. Some≈õvara ascended the throne, as is commonly believed, in 1126 or 1127. It is quite natural that a king in those days should require a few years for getting himself firmly seated on the throne, and for waging wars with neighbouring countries, which generally gave trouble when a kingdom changed hands. It seems therefore probable that the date given as Dhruv√¢·πÖka, referred to above, is the real date of composition.

Some≈õvara seems to be a powerful ruler, but very little is koown of his personal history. A few inscriptions were recorded during his reign but the information yielded by them is but meagre. What his religion was, it is difficult to ascertain. Here in the beginning his book opens with an obeisance to all the important deities of the Hindu Pantheon, namely, Ga·πáe≈õa, ≈õiva, Vis·πáu, BrahmƒÅ, Indra, etc. The very first ≈õloka refers to Ga·πáe≈õ√°, but we shall not be justified in calling him a ≈õaiva, because it is customary with authors of all sects to begin with an obeisance to Ga·πáe≈õa as the bestower of perfection and the remover of obstacles. The grant of MahƒÅma·πá·∏çale≈õvara M√¢rasi·πÉhadevarasa already referred to further makes us believe that Jainism was also encouraged in his time. Our conclusion therefore is that Some≈õvara also displayed the usual liberalism of Indian monarchs. The ≈õloka 105 on page 11 further strengthens this conclusion.

The MƒÅnasollƒÅsa is written in Anu·π£·π≠ubh metre, with occasional prose passages introduced in the middle. Its language is easy but florid. The work treats of many subjects and gives the maximum information in the minimum space. The work is designated by the author as the ‡§ú‡§ó‡§¶‡§æ‡§ö‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§Ø‡§™‡•Å‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡§ï‡§É, or a book which teaches the world, and the scope of the book is so extensive that it can rightly claim that epithet. An idea of the different subjects dealt with can be obtained form the table of contents; but we will mention here only a few interesting features among many that may be found in the book. It may be remembered that Some≈õvara was an orthodox Hindu king and the picture presented in his MƒÅnasollƒÅsa is of the glories, pomps and paraphernalia of a purely Indian court and royal household. The Western ChƒÅlukyas were never known to have been contaminated by the Muhammadan civilization, as they, it is believed, had been destroyed by the Hoysalas.

In this work sometimes the author gives even minute details like ‡§∏‡§ø‡§ï‡•ç‡§•‡§æ‡§¶‡§∑‡•ç‡§ü‡§ó‡•Å‡§£‡§Ç ‡§§‡§æ‡§Æ‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ç ( on ‡§Æ‡•Ç‡§∞‡•ç‡§§‡§ø‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§æ‡§® in ‡§á‡§∑‡•ç‡§ü‡§æ‡§™‡•Ç‡§∞‡•ç‡§§‡§æ‡§ß‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§Ø p. 9.) etc. and ‡§§‡•Å‡§≤‡§æ‡§≤‡§ï‡•ç‡§∑‡§£ ( p. 70.) and sometimes he omits the things that are really required, e. g., ‡§è‡§ï‡§æ ‡§§‡§æ‡§∞‡§æ etc. (p.106, ≈õl. 860) where the word TƒÅrƒÅ is not explained. The meanings of such words, however, may be found in other books like VasantarƒÅja ≈öƒÅkuna.

Among the two Vi·πÅ≈öatis contained in this volume, the first, generally speaking, describes the requisite qualifications and necessities of an ambitious king who desires to obtain and extend his dominions. The second Vi·πÉ≈öati mainly gives the ways and means of making the position of the king secure.

The first Vi·πÉ≈öati while dealing with the virtues of a king makes the T√ÆrthasnƒÅna an imperative necessity. In the TirthasnƒÅnƒÅdhyƒÅya the author mentions several T√Ærthas, namely, ≈öuklat√Ærtha*, Va√±jarƒÅ¬ß, Bh√Æmarathi, Ve·πáyƒÅ, the tributaries of the K·πõ·π£·πáƒÅ, etc, such as may reasonably be known to local people. He does not however mention Pu·π£kara near Ajmer, which is one of the greatest T√Ærthas. The mention of the TƒÅp√Æ river along with the famous and mighty rivers, Ganges, YamunƒÅ, NarmadƒÅ, Gautam√Æ, in the same ≈öloka shows that the author could not shake off the local influence while speaking of India in general. The omission of the KƒÅveri is worth noticing. It is probable also that in this particular he has followed the Brahma PurƒÅna which also mentions the rivers in the same strain.*

The three ≈õlokas treating of Jvara (p. 18, ≈õl. 188-190) are taken from an earlier work on medicine by VƒÅgbha·π≠a, but the other ≈õlokas have not been traced so far. In this AdhyƒÅya and in the AdhyƒÅyas of A≈õvavaidyaka and GajacikitsƒÅ it is worth noting that all the medicines mentioned are those prepared from medicinal plants. There is no mention of Bhasma, etc or medicines prepared from metals like iron, gold, etc.

In the first Vi·πÉ≈õati the longest is the 19th AdhyayƒÅ called the DinƒÅnƒÅthabandhubh·πõtyapo·π£a·πáƒÅdhyƒÅya. Here the recessity of appointing excellent physicians and free distribution of medicines is emphasized. Some≈õvara might have realized that people must necessarily love a king who takes care of them when they are in distress.

The second Vi·πÉ≈õati opens with an enumeration of the necessary qualifications of the king. RasƒÅyana comes next to make the king healthy and strong. Then he mentions the different officers required for the State, along with their requisite qualifications. Among the qualifications of the royal cook, one is Asa·πÉbhedya who cannot be bought over by the King’s enemies) and the other is KrtƒÅnnasya Parik·π£aka ( able to examine carefully the king’s food). This shows that the life of a king is perpetually in danger.

The line ‡§µ‡§ø‡§∂‡•á‡§∑‡•á‡§£ ‡§ö ‡§ï‡§æ‡§Ø‡§∏‡•ç‡§•‡•à‡§É ‡§™‡•Ä‡§°‡§ø‡§§‡§æ‡§É ‡§™‡§æ‡§≤‡§Ø‡•á‡§§‡•ç‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§ú‡§æ‡§É (p. 43 ≈õl.156.) indirectly shows that the author was well acquainted with the fact that people of the clerical profession are inclined to harass the public. It is quite possible also that he followed the previous writers on N√Æti (‡§®‡•Ä‡§§‡§ø) in this respect. On page 44 he fixes one-sixth of the produce of corn as the highest royal due, though in some cases it is made one-eighth or one-twelfth as a concession. The tax depends however on the productivity of the land. He fixes also one-sixth tax on honey and ghee, but does not formulate any taxation on other kinds of produce except to mention that a fruit graden is to be taxed according to its yield.

In those days the might of the king was calculated according to the number of elephants which he possessed. Hence the author mentions the forests which are the haunts of elephants, and minutely describes the varieties of the species and formulates means to catch them, train them, and make them fit for war.

It is believed by the writers on elephants that the elephant is a faithless animal, but our author does not subscribe to that opinion. The only kind of elephant which is faithless is the Sarpasattva while the rogue elephants come under the category of Pai≈õƒÅcasattva and RƒÅk·π£asasattvasamudbhava. The code of words given here for the training of elephants must have been in use in those days in MahƒÅrƒÅ·π£·π≠ra and Guzerat, as is evident from words such as ‡§¶‡•á‡§¶‡•á,‡§ò‡•á‡§ò‡•á, ‡§≠‡§≤‡•á, etc, but the code is different from the one that is now in use either at Baroda or Kolhapur. The elephant, though naturally timid in disposition, is able to destroy men in war if properly trained. The last lesson received by the elephant is how to destroy men (‡§∂‡§ø‡§ï‡•ç‡§∑‡§ø‡§§‡§Ç ‡§§‡•Å ‡§µ‡§ß‡§æ‡§µ‡§ß‡§ø p. 136, ≈õl. 1194). In this book no less than five methods of catching elephants are given. One of them is VƒÅribandha, which corresponds to the well-known Kheddah operations. A mention of this in MƒÅnasollƒÅsa shows that the method was in vogue in those days, but was afterwards forgotten, as may be seen from the following lines of G. P. Sanderson in his “Thirteen Year among the Wild Beasts of India pp. 101 and 103.

“Some of the Maharaja’s mahouts who were amongst my following had been accustomed to catch single elephants with trained females, and in pitfalls, but they had never heard of any one attempting the capture of a whole herd. It was said that Hyder had made a trial, a century before, in the Kakankote jungles, but had failed, and had recorded his opinion that no one would ever succeed and his curse upon any one that attempted to do so, on a stone still standing near the scene of his endeavours. Consequently all the true Mussulmans who were with me regarded the enterprise as hopeless, though they judiciously kept that opinion to themselves. "

(p. 101)

“I was determined to make the scheme succeed if possible, not only from my love of adventure and the necessity for executing what I had suggested to Government and undertaken to carry out, but from the desire to prove to several officers who considered the scheme to be the vision of a lunatic, that their croakings were rather the utterances of Bedlamites. Pleasantries appeared in the Bangalore papers regarding the probable effects the Kheddah operations would have on the price of salt, which it was represented was being laid in by me in large quantities for application to the caudal appendages of any elephants I happened to meet with “.

(p. 103).

The author Some≈õvara mentions ‡§¨‡•ç‡§∞‡§π‡•ç‡§Æ‡§æ‡§Ç‡§∂‡§ï elephant first. This is the only kind of elephant which is described as completely white (‡§ó‡•å‡§∞). Modern writers on elephants say that no such elephants are found:-

“I have never myself seen a really white one, nor have any of the experienced native hunters whom I have met “x x x Regarding the white elephants of which we read as forming the most cherished possessions of the King of Ava, I am unable to give any information”.

Sanderson p. 83.

“Occasionally so called white elephants are met with, which are really albinos, the dark pigment being absent from a larger or smaller area of the skin; in Burma and Siam such albinos being highly valued and considered as sacred or royal animals "

(Royal Natural History, by Lydekker Vol. II, p. 529.)

This kind of elephant may be ‡§ó‡•å‡§∞‡§∂‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§Æ‡§æ‡§§‡§®‡•ã‡§∂‡•ç‡§õ‡§µ‡§ø: mentioned on page 50, ≈õ1. 228. This is no doubt auspicious as it leads to victory. But this is not the white elephant described by Some≈õvara as ‡§¨‡•ç‡§∞‡§Æ‡•ç‡§π‡§æ‡§Ç‡§∂‡§ï. The author following previous writers might have mentioned various things, of course, which he never saw.

Two short sub-adhyƒÅyas viz: Nidhi and DhatuvƒÅda, RasƒÅyana in this book (pp. 59-61 and 63-64) are extre mely interesting. Enriching the Government treasury by the practice of alchemy is really astonishing. Not only ordinary people were keen on alchemy but Rajas and Maharajas also had recourse to such methods.

Where pearls and various kinds of gems are treated of, their defects also are not omitted, and mention is made of the devastating results of possessing such defective pearls and gems. On page 61, ≈õl. 426 Some≈õvara says that in this Kali-age pearls such as are found in oyster shells only are available. But he enumerates eight different sources of pearls, some altogether mythical, following perhaps the tradition of previous writers: In this connection he does not rest content with mentioning the sources only, but also minutely describes the kind of pearls produced from each source. He says in one place (p. 71 ≈õl. 471) that the king should not wear pearls which weigh more than two KƒÅla√±jas (equal to 60 Gu√±jƒÅs)

On page 79 things worth storing in a fort are mentioned. In ≈õlokas 551 to 555 the author deals with the necessity of keeping in stock stones and sand, serpents in earthen pots, and lions fixed to some convenient spot, and in fact, everything that may cause havoc in an hostile army.

On page 80, ≈õloka 561, we see the author advising kings not to put faith in the army formed of enemies, men, and not to allow them near his presence. He further advises that an army of this kind should always be put in the front in the event of war.

While referring to horses, Some≈õvara uses the word Yavanodbh≈´ta, by which are meant probably the Arabian horses. It appears that in his time horses from Sind, Arabia and the KƒÅmboja countries were famous. Among these the Arabian horses have maintained their reputation even now. He seems specially inclined towards the elephants of the Kalinga forests (‡§ï‡§æ‡§≤‡§ø‡§ô‡•ç‡§ó‡§µ‡§®‡§∏‡§Ç‡§≠‡§µ p. 136, ≈õl. 1194). He has also treated of the medicines to be administered to horses and elephants. On page 86 and 87 the description of fever in elephants etc is worth noting. There is no mention however of any medicine for fever in the case of elephants.

In the VasantarƒÅja ≈õƒÅkuna it is mentioned that there are five jewels among the ≈õakunas:‚Äî

‡§™‡•Ä‡§§‡§ï‡•Ä-‡§≠‡§∑‡§£ - ‡§ï‡§æ‡§ï-‡§™‡§ø‡§ô‡•ç‡§ó‡§≤‡§æ- ‡§ú‡§Æ‡•ç‡§¨‡•Å‡§ï‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§ø‡§Ø‡§§‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§ö ‡§™‡§û‡•ç‡§ö‡§Æ‡•Ä ‡•§

‡§™‡§§‡§¶‡§§‡•ç‡§∞ ‡§Æ‡•Å‡§®‡§ø‡§∏‡§§‡•ç‡§§‡§Æ‡•à‡§É ‡§∏‡§¶‡§æ ‡§ï‡•Ä‡§∞‡•ç‡§§‡•ç‡§Ø‡§§‡•á ‡§∂‡§ï‡•Å‡§®‡§∞‡§§‡•ç‡§®‡§™‡§û‡•ç‡§ö‡§ï‡§Æ‡•ç ‡••

( ‡§Ö‡§∞‡•ç‡§ö‡§®‡§æ‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§ø‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§ï‡§∞‡§£ ≈õl**.3 )**

Among them the Potaki is the chief. The ≈õloka runs thus -

**‡§Ø‡§§‡•ã‡§Ω‡§ñ‡§ø‡§≤‡•à‡§É ‡§∂‡§æ‡§ï‡•Å‡§®‡§∂‡§æ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•ç‡§∞‡§µ‡§ø‡§ú‡•ç‡§û‡•à‡§É **

‡§∂‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§Æ‡•ã‡§¶‡§ø‡§§‡§æ ‡§∏‡§∞‡•ç‡§µ‡§µ‡§ø‡§π‡§ô‡•ç‡§ó‡§Æ‡§æ‡§®‡§æ‡§Æ‡•ç ‡•§

‡§ß‡§æ‡§®‡§≠‡•Ç‡§§‡§æ X X X X X

(op. cit. p. 93)

All the five jewels are treated in this book. ≈õakunas like the Upa≈õruti are also mentioned. It may be pointed out in this connection that while giving the names of the Svaras of Pi·πÖgalƒÅ we considered it safer to follow the VasantarƒÅja ≈õ√¢kuna as all the different MSS have different and probably incorrect readings.

The chapters on polity give complete though succinct information about the royal policy. The three UpƒÅyas also are briefly treated, but the fourth, viz. Da·πá·∏ça is dwelt on at greater length.

It treats of the Caturasra Ko·π≠acakra and many other things dealing with astrology. It shows how the army should stand and how the kings, princes and other officers of the state should be posted. In the end the author steaks of Courts of Justice.

We take this opportunity of recording our cordial thanks and deep gratitude to HIS EXCELLENCY SIR MANUBHAI N. MEHTA Kt, C.S.I., M.A., L.L.B., Dewan Saheb of Baroda, for the keen interest he takes in the Series, and for the kind help rendered to us by obtaining a loan of the three Bikaner Durbar MSS on his personal responsibility. Our thanks are also due to the Bikaner Durbar for their courtesy in lending us these MSS; to the Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, for giving the loan of their MS; and to Pandit LB. Gandhi of our Library for assistance rendered by him in many directions, such as collating MSS, reading proofs, etc.

BARODA September 19,1925.

Introduction.

The second volume of the MƒÅnasollƒÅsa, the encyclopaedic work of the Western CƒÅlukya King Some≈õvara, is now offered to the Sanskrit knowing public. The volume contains the whole of the third Vi·πÅ≈õati in twenty chapters and part of the fourth Vi·πÅ≈õati comprising fifteen chapters. The third Vi·πÅ≈õati deals with the twenty kinds of Upabhogas or enjoyments, while the fourth treats of the twenty kinds of Vinodas or royal sports, out of which only fifteen are described in the present volume. The remaining five Vinodas and the last Vi·πÅ≈õati, namely, the Krƒ´·∏çƒÅvi·πÅ≈õati will appear in the third or the last volume. It is worthy of note that in the 4th Vi·πÅ≈õati the chapter on Music is the longest and equals in length the whole of the first volume. This, no doubt, bespeaks the great interest the royal author King Some≈õvara took in the science and perhaps also in the art of Music.

THE MSS. MATERIAL.

The present volume is prepared with the help of the following four MSS :‚Äî

A. Belongs to the Oriental Institute. It is a complete copy prepared with the help of three MSS.

B. Belongs to the Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona. It is incomplete. In this MS even the G·πõhopabhoga or the first AdhyƒÅya of the third Vi·πÅ≈õati is not complete.

D. Complete. It did not give much help in the preparation of this volume, since the subjects treated of in this volume are unusual; it is full of mistakes. It belongs to the Bikaner Durbar and we have a photostat copy of the same in our collection.

F. Complete but full of mistakes. This belongs to the Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona.

SUBJECT-MATTER.

The first AdhyƒÅya of the third Vi·πÅ≈õati opens with Muh≈´rta Jyotisa or the Science of Astrology for finding out auspicious moments while building new houses for princes, ladies of the harem and ministers. No information is, however, available here on town-planning or building of forts, since ostensibly the purpose of the Vi·πÅ≈õati is to describe the Upabhogas or royal enjoyments. It treats, nevertheless, of a few types of palaces like P·πõthvƒ´jaya, Muktako·πáa, Sarvatobhadra, Srƒ´vatsa etc. being fit objects of royal enjoyment.

THE CATU·π¢KAS.

As the Catu·π£kas1 allow good light and ventilation inside the house, every palace is here recommended to have at least one Catu·π£ka. Various kinds of palaces are mentioned here and their names differ with the number of Catu·π£kas, the number and direction of the Alindas, ≈õƒÅlƒÅs and Bhadras contained in them.

THE PALACES.

Houses with four ≈õƒÅlƒÅs, three ≈õƒÅlƒÅs, two ≈õƒÅlƒÅs and one ≈õƒÅlƒÅs are described afterwards. Sixteen kinds of palaces with one ≈õƒÅlƒÅ are distinguished. Dhruva is the first among the sixteen and Vijaya is the last among them. The result of living in these houses is the same as is conveyed by the very name given to these buildings e. g. Dhruva ‘permanency’, Vijaya ‘victory’ and so forth.

WORSHIP OF VƒÄSTU.

The king is required to worship the VƒÅstu or the site of the palace, a big square divided into 81 pƒÅdas and has to give specified offerings to the deities residing in those 81 pƒÅdas. The king has to perform this VƒÅstup≈´jƒÅ before building the palace and thereafter annually after the building is completed. The king’s palace may have one to nine stories. In the palace there must be certain very dark places to be illumined by Ma·πáidƒ´pas (or jewel-lamps) also entablatures (Matta-vƒÅra·πáas) with rich display of ivory, having pillars of gold or sandal wood, pavements of glass, crystal etc. and walls either made of crystal slabs looking like mirrors or made beautiful with wonderful pictures.

MATERIALS FOR PAINTING.

The author now deals with painters and painting, as also with the methods of preparing Vajralepa (adamantine paste), painting, brushes, pure and mixed colours. In his opinion there are only four ≈õuddha or original colours: white, red, yellow and black; and he recommends the use of ≈õa·πÖkha (conch) powder for white colour. He distinguishes three kinds of red colour and recommends Darada (red lead) for reddish brown, Alaktaka (red sap) for blood-red and Gairika (red chalk) for dark red. He prescribes HaritƒÅla (yellow orpiment) for the yellow colour and Kajjala (soot or lamp-black) for the black colour. While dealing with the Mi≈õravar·πáas he recommends gold to be used in showing the golden ornaments.

ICONOMETRY.

In the MƒÅnasollƒÅsa, very interesting details are given on portrait painting, which is dependent in the first place on the three principal lines, called the plumb lines here named as the Brahmas≈´tra and the two Pak·π£as≈´tras. The Brahmas≈´tra is the line which begins from the Ke≈õƒÅnta (forehead where the line of hair begins) and passes through the middle of the eyebrow, the tip of the nose, chin, chest and navel to the middle of the two feet. This line, therefore, marks the centre of the body from head to foot.
The two Pak·π£as≈´tras are usually six a·πÖgulas away from the Brahmas≈´tra on either side. They start from the Kar·πáƒÅnta (the top of the ear) and pass through the chin, the middle part of the knees, the outside skin and the second finger near the toe to the ground.

THE FIVE ATTITUDES.

With the variation of the distance between the central and side lines five different positions of the subject are obtained, in the same manner as the front, profile and three quarter positions are obtained in Western Art, The five positions are named in the MƒÅnasollƒÅsa as- ·πöju, Ardharju, SƒÅci, ArdhƒÅk·π£i and Bhittika. ·πöjusthƒÅna is the front position in which the distance between the central plumb line (Brahmas≈´tra) and the two Pak·π£as≈´tras i. e. side lines is six a·πÖgulas on both the sides. Ardha·πõjukasthƒÅna is that in which the distance from the Brahmas≈´tra to one Pak·π£as≈´tra is eight a·πÖgulas on one side and four a·πÖgulas on the other. The SƒÅcisthƒÅna is that in which the distance from the Brahmas≈´tra to one Paksas≈´tra is ten a·πÖgulas on one side and two a·πÖgulas on the other. The ArdhƒÅk·π£ikasthƒÅna is that in which the distance from the Brahmas≈´tra to one Pak·π£as≈´tra is eleven a·πÖgulas on one side and one a·πÖgula on the other. BhittikasthƒÅna is that in which only the Pak·π£as≈´tras are seen while the Brahma≈õutra disappears.

THE DEITIES.

Then he gives the DhyƒÅnas of the twenty-four forms of JagannƒÅtha or Vis·πáu beginning with Ke≈õava. All the twenty-four forms of Vis·πáu are endowed with four hands, carrying the well-known symbols of Vis·πáu, namely, the ≈õa·πÖkha (conch), Cakra (discus), GadƒÅ (mace) and Padma (lotus) in different orders.

For the four symbols of Vis·πáu the author here has used abbreviations: thus ≈õa for ≈õa·πÖkha, Ca for Cakra, Ga for GadƒÅ and Pa for Padma. Three abbreviations of symbols usually occur in each set of four letters where the fourth denotes the abbreviated name of the deity. The first letter shows the symbol in the right lower hand, the second in the right upper, the third in the left upper, while the fourth which is not mentioned denotes the left lower hand holding the remaining symbol. Thus the abbreviation means that the form bears clockwise Padma in the right lower hand, ≈õa·πÖkha in the right upper, Cakra in the left upper and GadƒÅ in the left lower (though not mentioned). The last letter ke indicates that the name of the form is Ke≈õava.

Then he gives the iconography of the eight-armed images of Hari, Trivikrama, N·πõsimha, RƒÅma and N·πõvarƒÅha and declares that these should be ten TƒÅlas in height while VƒÅmana should be of seven TƒÅlas.

The two works ≈õilparatna and MƒÅnasollƒÅsa agree so closely that one is tempted to believe that out of the two one must have borrowed from the other. The ≈õilaparatna of ≈örƒ´kumƒÅra being probably a work of the 16th century it is likely that it must have borrowed from the MƒÅnasollƒÅsa. It is, however, also probable that both of them might have borrowed from some earlier work which formed a common source.

In the first chapter the author deals with architecture, iconography, drawing, painting and cognate subjects. The M≈´rtis treated of in this work are : Ke≈õava etc. twenty-four forms of ‡§µ‡§ø‡§∑‡•ç‡§£‡•Å, ‡§π‡§∞‡§ø, ‡§§‡•ç‡§∞‡§ø‡§µ‡§ø‡§ï‡•ç‡§∞‡§Æ, ‡§µ‡§æ‡§Æ‡§®, ‡§∞‡§æ‡§Æ, ‡§®‡•É‡§µ‡§∞‡§æ‡§π, ‡§®‡§∞‡§∏‡§ø‡§Ç‡§π, ‡§Æ‡§§‡•ç‡§∏‡•ç‡§Ø and ‡§ï‡•Ç‡§∞‡•ç‡§Æ; ‡§¨‡•ç‡§∞‡§π‡•ç‡§Æ‡§¶‡•á‡§µ, ‡§Æ‡§π‡§æ‡§¶‡•á‡§µ in human form as in ‡§ó‡§ú‡§æ‡§∏‡•Å‡§∞‡§µ‡§ß, as in ‡§§‡•ç‡§∞‡§ø‡§™‡•Å‡§∞‡§¶‡§æ‡§π as ‡§∏‡•ç‡§µ‡§ö‡•ç‡§õ‡§®‡•ç‡§¶‡§≠‡•à‡§∞‡§µ, as ‡§Ö‡§∞‡•ç‡§ß‡§®‡§æ‡§∞‡•Ä‡§∂‡•ç‡§µ‡§∞ as ‡§â‡§Æ‡§æ‡§Æ‡§π‡•á‡§∂‡•ç‡§µ‡§∞ and as ‡§π‡§∞‡§ø‡§π‡§∞, ‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§§‡§ø‡§ï‡§∏‡•ç‡§µ‡§æ‡§Æ‡•Ä, ‡§ó‡§£‡•á‡§∂, ‡§ï‡§æ‡§≤‡•Ä, ‡§Æ‡§π‡§ø‡§∑‡§æ‡§∏‡•Å‡§∞‡§Æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§ø‡§®‡•Ä with eight hands, ‡§á‡§®‡•ç‡§¶‡•ç‡§∞, ‡§Ö‡§ó‡•ç‡§®‡§ø, ‡§Ø‡§Æ, ‡§∞‡§æ‡§ï‡•ç‡§∑‡§∏‡•á‡§®‡•ç‡§¶‡•ç‡§∞, ‡§µ‡§∞‡•Å‡§£, ‡§µ‡§æ‡§Ø‡•Å, ‡§ï‡•Å‡§¨‡•á‡§∞, ‡§à‡§∂‡§æ‡§®, ‡§Æ‡§æ‡§§‡•É‡§ï‡§æs, ‡§∂‡•ç‡§∞‡•Ä, ‡§®‡§æ‡§ó, ‡§¶‡•à‡§§‡•ç‡§Ø, ‡§¶‡§æ‡§®‡§µ, ‡§™‡§ø‡§∂‡§æ‡§ö, ‡§µ‡•á‡§§‡§æ‡§≤, ‡§ï‡•ç‡§∑‡•á‡§§‡•ç‡§∞‡§™‡§æ‡§≤, ‡§ï‡§æ‡§Æ‡§¶‡•á‡§µ, ‡§∏‡•Ç‡§∞‡•ç‡§Ø, ‡§ö‡§®‡•ç‡§¶‡•ç‡§∞, ‡§≠‡•å‡§Æ, ‡§¨‡•Å‡§ß, ‡§ó‡•Å‡§∞‡•Å, ‡§∂‡•Å‡§ï‡•ç‡§∞, ‡§∂‡§®‡§ø, ‡§∞‡§æ‡§π‡•Å and ‡§ï‡•á‡§§‡•Å.

At the end of this chapter he gives a full description of two animals, namely, the horse and the elephant but does not mention the bull which is found in the ≈öilparatna of ≈örƒ´kumara. The deities already mentioned seem to be the favourite gods of the time. Their forms without exception are pleasant; loathsome or dreadfull pictures which are likely to cause depression of spirits are not allowed to be drawn in palaces, as everything pleasant and attractive must be before the eye of a king to keep him cheerful. In this connection it may be remembered that the UttararƒÅmacarita of Bhavabh≈´ti clearly shows the tragic effect the unpleasant pictures produced on the minds of RƒÅma and Sƒ´tƒÅ. On this point further information may also be obtained from the Yogag·πõhacitra as cited in the Ha·π≠hayogapradƒ´pikƒÅ. The sight of ≈öma≈öanƒÅ and Naraka, for instance, makes a man think of the transitoriness of the world. He is likely to develop a strong sense of VairƒÅgya or non-attachment which is dangerous for a person who has to guide the destinies of a kingdom. In short, the pictures must be fitting to the gay atmosphere of the palace. It, therefore, stands to reason that everything in the palace must be such as will keep the king always cheerful. There is a passage, in the MƒÅnasollƒÅsa to show that the main purpose of the pictures should be to remove the anguish from the heart.

VARIETIES OF PICTURES.

The author then proceeds to classify the different kinds of pictures and explain the various technical terms. The exact copy of an object as we find in a reflection is named by him as Viddha while mere resemblance is called Aviddha. The picture that expresses the Rasas like ≈ö·πõngƒÅra is called a BhƒÅvacitra while the one with bright colours is named as Db≈´licitra. It is worthy of note that here King Some≈õvara proudly describes himself as ‡§ö‡§ø‡§§‡•ç‡§∞‡§µ‡§ø‡§¶‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§µ‡§ø‡§∞‡§û‡•ç‡§ö‡§ø‡§®‡•ç (‡§µ‡§ø‡§Ç. ‡•©-‡•Ø‡•¶‡•´ ) - the creator or master of the art of drawing and painting.

To prevent smoke nuisance from the ‡§π‡•ã‡§Æ‡§∂‡§æ‡§≤‡§æ in the palace he recommends the construction of latticed windows etc. The necessity of having a ‡§ö‡§§‡•Å‡§∑‡•ç‡§ï in the palace and the passage i. e. ‡§Ö‡§≤‡§ø‡§®‡•ç‡§¶ shows that the old engineers had a good grasp of the problems of light and ventilation.

The king is advised also to spend different seasons in different types of palaces which are constructed differently to suit the seasons and the variable weather. The author is particular in having four palaces for the four seasons, i. e. the spring, the summer, the winter and the rainy season.

Then begins the chapter entitled the SnƒÅnopabhoga or ’the enjoyment of bath’. The king’s person, he says, should first be anointed with fragrant oil and then massaged by expert wrestlers well-versed in the art of massaging. An ointment prepared with fragrant unguents like Kos·π≠ha etc. in water or KƒÅ√±jikƒÅ is applied afterwards to the body for rubbing and cleaning the skin. A Khali (a special preparation of an ointment of wheat-flour etc. in ƒÄranƒÅlas) is then applied to remove grease from the skin and it serves the same purpose as the modern soap. Young women then pour over the head water from golden jars made fragrant by various scented things. The scented oil of ƒÄmalakƒ´ is then applied to the hair; sometimes scented turmeric is applied in addition. The oil and turmeric are then removed with warm water and the body is rubbed vigorously with a dry towel. Finally the removal of wet clothings completes the elaborate process of a royal bath.

The bath over, the king should put on a pair of sandals made of ≈örƒ´par·πáƒ´ or Harichandana wood or of leather which covers only the front portion of the foot according to convenience. This is called the PƒÅdukƒÅbhoga or the enjoyment of sandals.

Coming out of the SnƒÅnag·πõha (bath room) the king should enter the Sukha-Mandir (pleasure hall). He should then summon the officer-in-charge of TƒÅmb≈´la ‘betel leaves’ and take from him one TƒÅmb≈´la. For this purpose excellent areca nuts are obtained from places like VanavƒÅsƒ´. A slice from the top of the nut is first removed and then it is dried in the shade. One fourth of this nut is used in preparing the TƒÅmb≈´la which consists of fifty-two yellowish betel leaves with their ends removed. The ingredients used for the TƒÅmb≈´la include pearl oyster, the Is’ƒÅvƒÅsa camphor, Kast≈´rƒ´ (musk) and various other sweet smelling things.

The author then proceeds to describe the vilepanas or unguents to render the skin soft, clean and fair. Different vilepanas are prescribed for different seasons. The vilepana called SƒÅndhya is designed to remove the smell of perspiration. In this chapter the author deals with the tests of Chandana and Kast≈´rƒ´ which are used in the summer and the rainy season respectively. The lepana known as pullinga is prescribed for the cold season (Hemanta and ≈õi≈õira) exclusively. The colour of the vilepana is required to be harmonized with the dress which also changes according to seasons.

The author next deals with the interesting topic of Vastropabhoga or the “enjoyment of garments”. The chapter opens with astrological observations on the auspicious and inauspicious moments for putting on new dress and gives the results arising therefrom. The author incidentally observes that for putting on new clothing on ceremonial occasions like the G·πõhotsava or marriage, it is not necessary to observe the Muh≈´rta or auspicious moments. After applying the vilepana to his body the king should call the officer-in-charge of the royal ward-robe and order him to bring excellent clothes of cotton or silk woven with silver or golden threads of various kinds and colours brought from different countries and wear them.

In the Vasanta (spring) season the king is asked to put on silk or cotton clothes which are thin and charming. In Grƒ´sma (summer) he should wear clothes of white colour. But if he wants to wear woollen clothes of white colour they must be very thin, soft and beautiful. In the rainy season he should wear red, pink, reddish and dark-red clothes made in an attractive style. In the ·π°arad (autumn) season he should wear very thin clothes dyed with safflower or lac. In the cold season, he should wear woollen clothes of various kinds. On the whole the king should according to different seasons wear thin, costly and beautiful clothes of various colours to suit his own complexion.

Then comes the MƒÅlyabhoga (enjoyment of garlands). After putting on fine clothes he should wear garlands made of various kinds of flowers. After MƒÅlyopabhoga comes the Bh≈´·π£opabhoga (enjoyment of ornaments). While talking of diamonds he uses the line ‡§µ‡•à‡§∞‡§æ1‡§ï‡§∞‡§≠‡§µ‡§Ç ‡§µ‡§ú‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ç ‡§µ‡§ø‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§ú‡§æ‡§§‡•Ä‡§Ø‡§Æ‡•Å‡§§‡•ç‡§§‡§Æ‡§Æ‡•ç ‡•§ which means that the diamond produced in the ‡§µ‡•à‡§∞‡§æ‡§ï‡§∞ mine is of the highest (‡§¨‡•ç‡§∞‡§æ‡§π‡•ç‡§Æ‡§£) quality. Some of the ornaments described in the MƒÅnasollƒÅsa may be said to be current in modern times e. g. the ornament called SƒÅrikƒÅ, for instance, is current now and it is called Sari in MarƒÅthi. Though fashions in ornaments are always in a flux, we can nevertheless find them used even in modern days. Ornaments like Key≈´ra etc. are also found in both Northern and Southern India bearing either the same or an entirely different name. It is, however, noteworthy that there is no mention of any ornament for the nose which very probably was introduced after the advent of the Muhammedans.

Then comes the ChƒÅmarabhoga (enjoyment of a chauri in MarƒÅthi) or a bushy tail of the chƒÅmara used as a fly-whisk or a fan. Then comes the ƒÄsthƒÅnabhoga (enjoyment of holding the Darbar). The king should sit on the throne placed in the assembly hall (Darbar hall) and ask his Pratƒ´hƒÅra to send a SarvƒÅvƒÅhana (general invitation) to attend the Darbar. In response to the general invitation, first the women of the harem are allowed to enter the assembly hall. They come in palanquins fitted with curtains and accompanied by staff bearers (attendants on women’s apartments) who carry sticks made of teak wood or cane. The chief duty of the staff bearer is to cry out “Go away, Go away” in order to make room for the palanquin to pass through crowded roads. The ladies of the harem, according to their positions, occupy their respective seats on all sides of the throne except the front. Their eyes are generally turned towards the king or they cast occasional glances at him in order that he may be in a pleasant mood. Other invited ladies come to the assembly hall on horses, mares or on foot. Thus women of different ages enter the hall finely dressed and richly adorned with ornaments of gold and jewels. Here the author incidentally gives striking characteristics of the women belonging to different nationalities adjoining his territory. He carefully describes the women of Kuntala, Dravida, MahƒÅrƒÅ·π£·π≠ra, ƒÄndhra and Gurjara but does not mention those of his own territory. The countries mentioned in this connection in a minor way fix the boundary of the territory over which Some≈õvara ruled.

In this connection peculiarities in dress off ‡§¶‡•ç‡§∞‡§µ‡§ø‡§° and ‡§ó‡•Å‡§∞‡•ç‡§ú‡§∞ women as stated in the body of the text, remind one of the beautiful ‡§∂‡•ç‡§≤‡•ã‡§ï quoted in the commentary of the ‡§ï‡§æ‡§µ‡•ç‡§Ø‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§ï‡§æ‡§∂ text “‡§ï‡§æ‡§Æ‡§ø‡§®‡•Ä‡§ï‡•Å‡§ö‡§ï‡§≤‡§∂‡§µ‡§§‡•ç ‡§ó‡•Ç‡§¢‡§Ç ‡§ö‡§Æ‡§§‡•ç‡§ï‡§∞‡•ã‡§§‡§ø. The commentator seems to be a Northerner as he does not clearly understand the difference between the ‡§Ü‡§®‡•ç‡§ß‡•ç‡§∞ and ‡§¶‡•ç‡§∞‡§µ‡§ø‡§° ladies and confounds all the southern ladies with ‡§Ü‡§®‡•ç‡§ß‡•ç‡§∞ ladies. Hence a perfect agreement is seen between the two lines: ‡§ï‡§æ‡§∂‡•ç‡§ö‡§ø‡§¶‡•ç ‡§¶‡•ç‡§∞‡§µ‡§ø‡§°‡§ï‡§æ‡§Æ‡§ø‡§®‡•ç‡§Ø‡§É ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§ï‡§æ‡§∂‡§ø‡§§‡§™‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ß‡§∞‡§æ‡§É ‡•§ and ‡§®‡§æ‡§®‡•ç‡§ß‡•ç‡§∞‡•Ä‡§™‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ß‡§∞ ‡§á‡§µ‡§æ‡§§‡§ø‡§§‡§∞‡§æ‡§Ç ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§ï‡§æ‡§∂‡§É ‡•§ Similarly, the description of the dress of GujarƒÅti ladies stated by these different authorities exactly tallies in sense.

Gujarati ladies of to-day have the uttarƒ´ya (upper garment) put on in such a way that the left hand is kept visible. This seems to be the custom of the ƒÄndhra ladies also, so much so, that it attracted the attention of the King Some≈õvara. It is noteworthy, however, that he gives no special characteristics of Canarese women although he is himself a Canarese king, loving Canarese language and script and ruling over a Canarese speaking country. Either he identifies ‡§ï‡•Å‡§®‡•ç‡§§‡§ï with ‡§ï‡§∞‡•ç‡§£‡§æ‡§ü‡§ï or he omits ‡§ï‡§∞‡•ç‡§£‡§æ‡§ü‡§ï of because he thinks it to be quite a well known thing. The Western ‡§ö‡§æ‡§≤‡•Å‡§ï‡•ç‡§Øs are known as ‡§ï‡•Å‡§®‡•ç‡§§‡§≤‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§≠‡•Ås i. e. the lords of ‡§ï‡•Å‡§®‡•ç‡§§‡§≤ country with its capital at ‡§ï‡§≤‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§£‡§™‡•Å‡§∞ or ‡§ï‡§≤‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§£‡•Ä. Now-a-days ‡§Æ‡§∞‡§æ‡§†‡•Ä seems to be the vernacular of this country. All these women are taken as an ornament of the Darbar. It seems that some are Purdah ladies while others are not; they can attract the attention of whosoever happens to look at them.

After the entry of the ladies of the harem and other invited women, come all the princes modestly bowing to the king and take their respective seats in front of him. The Purohita (priest) dressed in white takes his seat near the princes. Then come the AmƒÅtya, Mantri, Sachiva etc. who form part of the second of the seven A·πÖgns (limbs of the kingdom). They sit in their proper places when ordered by the king. Then come the Ma·πá·∏çalƒÅdhƒ´≈õvaras (rulers or Governors of districts or provinces) and SƒÅmantƒÅmƒÅtyakas (the feudatory princes or their ministers) who are required to sit in front of the king to the right and left in their proper places as ordered by the king. Then enter the officers of the state and are seated in their respective seats. Here the author gives an elaborate list of officers who are classified under three main heads of Dharma, Artha and KƒÅma. The names of the different officers mentioned are interesting as showing the administrative machinery of the author, King Some≈õvara and incidentally of the age to which the king belonged. The designations, significant in themselves, are given below:‚Äî (1) KosƒÅdhikƒÅrin, apparently the Accountant General of to-day (2) NiskƒÅdhikƒÅrin, the Treasury officer or the mint officer who is actually in charge of the Niskas i.e. gold coins (3) M≈´lyƒÅdhikƒÅrin, probably the officer who fixes the wages or salary (4) ArghƒÅdhikƒÅrin, probably for fixing the value of articles to be sold in the bazar (5) KarmƒÅdhikƒÅrin, probably the officer in charge of the KarmakƒÅ·πá·∏ça (performance of religious duties) (6) VidyƒÅdhik√†rin, the officer in charge of the recognised fourteen VidyƒÅs while (7) the ≈õƒÅstrƒÅdhikƒÅrin may be in charge of the other ≈õƒÅstras (depart- ments of knowledge), such as sciences of politics, agriculture, music, astronomy, astrology, palmistry, medicine, Dhanurveda, etc. The word (8) ChitrƒÅdhikƒÅrin shows that there was an officer in charge of the picture gallery. (9) M·πõgƒÅdhikƒÅrin is in charge of the deer etc. and the beasts of prey, while (10) PaksƒÅdhik»Érin may be the man in charge of the aviary. (11) The A·πÖgƒÅdhikƒÅrins are the body guards or A. D. C.s and (12) PrƒÅ·πá»ÉdhikƒÅrins are the physicians. (13) GhƒÅsƒÅdhik√†rin may perhaps be the officer in charge of the grass or forest department. (14) SudhƒÅdhikƒÅrin seems to be the officer in charge of the white-washing, painting or decoration department. The names of the (15) Vastr√°dhikƒÅrin and (16) PhalƒÅdhik√°rin have come twice in the list. (17) Par·πáƒÅdhikƒÅrin may be the officer in charge of the betel nut or garden department. (18) Var·πáƒÅdhikƒÅrin seems to be the officer whose duty it may be to see whether all the Var·πáas (Brahma·πáa. K·π£atriya, Vai≈õya and ≈õudra) behave properly according to the established customs. (19) Du·π£·π≠ƒÅdhikƒÅrin seems to be the Jail Superintendent. There is no engineering department but we think that (20) DurgƒÅdhikƒÅrin may include engineers also. It is posible that there was an engineering department, otherwise it was not possible for the author to introduce a long chapter on buildings in the beginning of the third Vi·πÅ≈õati. This department may form one of the departments under the DurgƒÅdhikƒÅrin or Gr√°mƒÅdhikƒÅrin or De≈õƒÅdhikƒÅrin or perhaps the SudhƒÅdhikƒÅrin. All officers wear fine coats of long sleeves embroidered with gold, turbans and golden ornaments. Betel-nut-bearers and trustworthy swordsmen (A. D. C.s) who have conquered their passions should stand attentively near the king.

Then comes a list of professional people who utter the words “Victory to the King”. It is worthy of note that in this list along with Bha·π≠·π≠a, ChƒÅra·πáa, Bandi, VaitƒÅlika and ChƒÅ·π≠ukƒÅra are included poets, astrologers, VƒÅdis (plaintiffs, complainants), VƒÅgƒ´s’as-orators, PƒÅ·π≠hakas- readers of the Pur»Énas and Kathakas-story tellers, that is to say, the modern Harikƒ´rtana people. All these, therefore, appear to be the servants of his private department. The A·πÖkas (those who fight with their enemies by the same weapon) are also included in this list. The whole assembly in the Darbar Hall should eagerly look at the king as they would look at the moon when it rises on the first day of the month. The king then should order the door-keeper to summon the smaller kings who have come there to seek his protection to appear before him. Immediately on entering the hall the new-comer should prostrate himself before the throne. The king, thereupon, should sympathetically ask the new-comer to get up and take his appointed seat. When a ruling king seeks protection, a seat befitting his position may be given to him with due respect. He should please him with kind words and present him fine clothes, gold ornaments, jewels, horses and elephants, villages, cities or even small countries and make him stay in the best houses. In the same way, he should please the princes, ministers, warriors, officers, scholars, favourites and those who can amuse and excite mirth! Then leaving the Darbar Hall he should go to the pleasure house in the company of women.

Next follows the enjoyment of children. The author in this section deals with the Sa·πÅskƒÅras like GarbhƒÅdhƒÅna, Pu·πÅsavana, Sƒ´manta, JƒÅtakarma, NƒÅmakara·πáa and incidentally gives detailed information on this subject called from Jyotisa, Vaidyaka and Dharma≈õƒÅstra works.

King Some≈õvara is an eminent authority on music as can be seen from the introductory stanzas of Sa·πÖgƒ´taratnƒÅkara and the first ≈öloka of the second AdhyƒÅya of Sa·πÖgƒ´tasamayasƒÅra. While dealing with the NƒÅmakara·πáa ceremony the king advises that the male child should be named with suffixes such as simha, malla, bƒÅhu, pƒÅla, etc. This chapter shows that the king was very affectionate and tender-hearted.

EDUCATION OF THE PRINCE.

After performing the Upanayana ceremony in the eighth or eleventh year the prince should be taught one of the Vedas, the use of weapons and various other sciences. How many subjects the princes had to learn is given on page 110. They are required to be trained by experts and repeatedly examined by experts. When the king is pleased with the progress of the princes he should embrace them and honour them with sweet words and presents and the teachers should be presented with cows, towns or even villages. After educating the princes properly the king should get them married. The marriage customs also are given in the book. They appear like the present MarƒÅtha customs as observed in the royal family at Baroda excepting perhaps the use of ‡§ú‡•Ä‡§∞‡§ïs. p. 113. The MarƒÅtha bridegroom and the bride before ‡§ï‡§®‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§¶‡§æ‡§® are brought together face to face with a screen between them and the recitation of ‡§Æ‡§ô‡•ç‡§ó‡§≤‡§æ‡§∑‡•ç‡§ü‡§ï are goes on. They put garlands on the neck of each other after the removal of the screen put between them. The custom appears somewhat like that of the ƒÄ≈õvalƒÅyanas and resembles the one given in the Prayogaratna of NƒÅrƒÅya·πáabha·π≠·π≠a. How the prince proceeds to the bride’s house is not given but the author has described the procession from the bride’s house to the bridegroom’s residence after the marriage ceremony is over. It should be accompanied by hundreds of torches while the music of the Pa√±chamahƒÅ≈õabdas is going on. The use of the compound Pa√±chamahƒÅ≈õabdas in the line-

The investment with the honour of Pa√±chamahƒÅ≈õabdas was always granted by mighty kings to the most important citizens of th e state. No such honour seems to have been given in the days of the Moghul and Maratha Ascendency.

Then comes the Annabhoga. In this chapter he has given the names of a great many articles of food and the directions as to the preparations of various dishes. The king should take his food along with his sons, grandsons, relations, lords, A. D. C.s and his special private servants. In this chapter the author gives methods of preparing vegetarian as well as non-vegetarian articles of food. Many names appear as being current in Canarese, Tamil, etc. while there are others which still survive in MarƒÅthi. Thus Dho≈õƒÅ, Idali, etc. are even to-day found in Canarese and Tamil while dishes like ‡§Æ‡§£‡•ç‡§°-‡§Æ‡§æ‡§Ç‡§°‡•á, ‡§™‡•ã‡§≤‡§ø‡§ï‡§æ-‡§™‡•ã‡§≥‡•Ä, ‡§µ‡§ü‡§ø‡§ï‡§æ-‡§µ‡§°‡•á, ‡§ï‡§ü‡§ï‡§∞‡•ç‡§£- ‡§ï‡§°‡§ï‡§£‡•á‡§Ç are known to the MarƒÅthas. The method of using Hingu (asafoetida) as given in the MƒÅnasollƒÅsa is not to use it in small quantities as is now being done usually but by using Hi·πÖgu water. Water can give the smell of Hingu if powder of Hi·πÖgu is mixed with water and kept standing for some time. This use of Hi·πÖgu is not known in Northern India. The process of Hi·πÖgudh≈´pa is also described here which resembles Phoda·πái (MarƒÅthi) or VaghƒÅra (GujarƒÅti) of modern days.

While describing non-vegetarian preparations the method of removing the hair of a pig is given. The animal should first be covered with a white piece of cloth. Boiling water should then be poured on the body of the boar with the help of a Ga·πá·∏çaka (a vessel used for taking water from a big earthern pot) with a handle slowly till the hair are so shaken from the roots that they can be easily removed by hands. The remainder may then be removed with the help of a pair of scissors. Another method of removing the hair from the body is to besmear it with mud and burn the skin with fire made of grass. While treating of the preparation of ‡§ñ‡§£‡•ç‡§°s of ‡§µ‡§™‡§æ he says that ‡§µ‡§™‡§æ should be kept in the form of a roll like ‡§™‡§û‡•ç‡§ö‡§æ‡§ô‡•ç‡§ó.

In the opinion of the author dishes prepared in earthern vessels taste well. Peculiar mice living in the fields near rivers are also included in the non-vegetarian food. After describing the vegetarian dishes the author proceeds to describe the preparations of milk and curds. Then he refers to the manner in which the district officers are to be treated while at dinner. The king himself should be supplied with a golden dish having a bunch of golden vessels for curries. The king with his face turned towards the east should sit on a cushion with a white napkin spread from the navel to the knee. Thus the use of napkins at the time of dinner appears to be an old custom of rich men or princes in India. In the beginning the king should take rice with ‡§Æ‡•Å‡§¶‡•ç‡§ó‡§∏‡•Ç‡§™ and ghee; in the middle sweetmeats i. e. dishes prepared with milk, sugar and ghee should be eaten. Then he should take fruits, sweet as well as sour, cold drinks, S’ikhari·πáƒ´ and thick curds. Lastly, he should take buttermilk and salt with rice, which may be followed by milk and sugar. No mention of Ra·πÖgƒÅvali or artistic designs made of coloured powders by the side of the dish is made by the author.

The king is then recommended to change foods and drinks in accordance with the needs of different seasons. He is asked to eat for instance, pungent things in spring, sweet and cold things in summer, salted things in the rainy season, sweet things in autumn, greasy and hot things in Hemanta and hot and cold things in winter. It is probable that this routine is fixed in accordance with medical laws in order to counteract the Dosa which becomes predominant in a particular season. Then comes the ‡§™‡§æ‡§®‡•Ä‡§Ø‡§≠‡•ã‡§ó or the enjoyment of drinking water.

The king is asked to sip water very often during meals. This the author thinks, imparts taste to the food and helps digestion. Some≈õvara’s rule regarding the drinking of water is rather peculiar. He recommends that whenever the king is thirsty he should drink water and should never think of time and circumstances, that is to say, whether it is morning or mid-night or whether he is with a full or an empty stomach. In this respect the author recommends that the rules of medical science may be violated. Compare with this the rules like the following as found in medical works : ‚Äî

Then he gives the nine varieties of water of which Ha·πÅsodaka is known in other medical books as A·πÅ≈õ≈´daka. He does not define the Audbhida water which is given in BhƒÅvaprakƒÅ≈õa as ‚Äî
